GCA NTUS (Not the Usual Suspects) Semi Annual Angel Investing Forum
British Columbia. High net worth individuals who have accrued wealth in real estate, mining, manufacturing, forestry, and other ‘traditional’ industries.

Andrew Jones, 6043073772, 210 – 415 Cordova St, Vancouver, BC, Technology focused transaction advisor / investment banker; multiple angel investments historical and active; 10 major financings closed since firm inception.
Brent Holliday, CEO, brent@garibaldicapital.com Andrew Jones, CFO, andrew@garibaldicapital.com

Bi-annual (every 6 months) event. 10 highly curated companies pitch for 10 minutes each, to an audience of highly curated angels that we consider to be ‘Not the Usual Suspects’ as angel investors, having achieved financial success in other industries but having expressed a clear interest in angel investing in growth / technology companies at the Seed I / Seed II stage.. Mission: To provide a zero fee, confidential, highly curated forum for both angels and CEOs to connect – formally during the pitch phase, and informally, socially, thereafter (during the hosted reception phase)
To seek out lead sponsors to cover the full costs of: venue, food, marketing / promotion, and investor education.
We are starting a NTUS Toronto in 2016. It will likely be in conjunction with the new/expanded 111 Kings incubator space.

VA Angels Kelowna Holdings LTD.
The Okanagan Valley, British Columbia

Randy Lennon, 403-831-9720, Kelowna@VaAngels.Com, Randy Lennon, CEO , is a 40 year entrepreneur who has founded and built successful enterprises in the fields of newspaper publishing, television and radio, recording artist management, retail, advertising, marketing and the internet. He has also worked as a police officer, regional television and national radio talk show host, starred in a situation comedy pilot, and worked as a special advisor to the leader of a major national political party in Ottawa. His recording artists have won US Gold and Platinum Albums as well as the Juno Award in Canada. In the field of media, Mr. Lennon founded the Spruce Grove Examiner at age 19, building the company to a chain of four weekly newspapers serving the Edmonton market. As Chairman of the Privatization Committee of the board of directors of Access Television Network, he oversaw the first successful privatization of a public television broadcaster in North America. His crowning achievement in the area was the development of “The Biz Brainstorm” workshop and radio show series that garnered back-to-back nominations for the prestigious Ernst and Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award.In addition to serving as CEO for Candor, Mr. Lennon is managing director with Calgary, Vancouver and Regina based Meridian International Merchant Capital, providing capital and corporate finance advisory services to companies operating internationally. Meridian recently arranged financing that facilitated the purchase of the Phoenix Coyotes by a group of primarily Alberta investors. He is also the President of VA Angels Kelowna and Phoenix chapters, one of Canada’s most active Angel Investor Network (also in Calgary, Edmonton and Winnipeg). VA Angels brings together accredited investors with early stage companies to grow through investing capital, guidance, and mentorship. VA Angels recently celebrated its 100th investee company and over the 13 years members invested over $38 million.
Randy Lennon, President Samantha Milligan, Secretary

VA Angels Kelowna is a subsidiary of VA Angels. VA Angels is one of Canada’s largest and most active Angel Network, boasting 5 Chapters, over 150 Members and a 12 year track record . Mission: VA Angels Kelowna’s Vision is to Educate and Empower Accredited Investors for the Purposes of Promoting and Growing the Angel Industry within The Okanagan Valley. Our Mission is to grow our Membership to 50 Members by December 2016 to provide our Companies with access to a dynamic and high quality group of accredited Investors.

Constant Sales & Marketing Efforts and regular Membership Referral Programs. Also providing a quality Forum experience for both the Investor and Entrepreneur which will manifest it’s own perpetual growth.

VA Angels is proud to be a part of a Master Organization which promotes this form of Networking and Collaboration. We are also eager to attend industry related events to connect with all other Networks outside of our parent brand.

VA Angels Kelowna would be interested in launching a new website (Branded to match our parent organization) located at the URL OkanaganAngels.Ca for the sole purposes of educating accredited investors on the value of Angel Investing and promoting the industry within the goals and the objectives laid out by the purposes of the grant funding. ($2,495+GST). We then would like to conduct a monthly Digital Marketing Campaign which consists of SEO (Search Engine Optimization), Google Adwords, Social Media Marketing and RTB (Real Time Bidding) for the purposes of driving traffic from HNW Accredited individuals to this Educational website where the final conversion is application to our Chapter. Based in a Monthly Budget of $1,595 for this Campaign we project 27 – 35 new Member Applicants over the course of 12 months. Total Annual Project Cost - $21,635

VA Angels Kelowna would like to host a one day Free (To accredited investors and Yacht Club Members) Angel Investment Workshop promoting Angel Investing in the Okanagan Valley hosted at the Kelowna Yacht Club. The cost of Hosting and Catering for this event is $5,000 We will utilize the Marketing Budget and resources from Project #1 to Promote this event Online.

VA Angels Kelowna would like to Publish and Distribute an Okanagan Valley Angel Investing Industry Magazine. This would be printed Quarterly and would also become a revenue generating Project after the second Issue. The Cost of Printing, Production and Distribution of this Project would be $9,550 per issue for the Spring and Summer Issues. Totaling $19,100 of the Grant Funding. After 2 Issues it will be self sustaining (with advertising revenues). Considerable planning has been done on this project (see attached mock-up and branding) and Samantha and Randy both have considerable experience in publishing. **Please note the attached sample says Canada’s Angel Investment Magazine but will be changed to The Okanagan Valley’s Angel Investing Magazine. (This can be modified during any issue for the purpose of expansion when needed). The Magazine will be a free coffee table publication which will be hand distributed throughout the Okanagan Valley to highly targeted areas where accredited investors work, play and shop. Distribution will include (but not be limited to) The Kelowna Yacht Club, luxury car dealership’s (waiting areas), and high profile legal offices. There will also be a targeted mailing list of Investors and subscribers as well. The goals of the project are as follows; -To grow the size of the Angel community in the Okanagan -To assist in increasing the amount of Angel funds received by Canadian companies -To grow our membership to 50 Members by Dec 2016 -To provide a vehicle to help NACO collect Investment Data -To improve communication & information flow of the Angel Industry -To be an educational resource to the Angel Community -To promote Angel Events
VA Angels Kelowna would like to host a Spring Members Social Gathering for the purpose of Member Referral & Awareness. This will be held in May 2016 and Cost $3,200 with Catering and Marketing.

TEC Venture Angels is a partnership between TEC Edmonton and VA Angels. This merger has allowed for an increase in pitch forums as well given more exposure to the public of the entrepreneurial start up space. This aids in both member recruitment as well as increased opportunities for entrepreneurs to pitch their company. TEC Venture Angels is run by not-for-profit business incubator and accelerator TEC Edmonton. TEC Edmonton screens and assists start-up companies wishing to approach TEC Venture Angels for investment capital. All investments are either done directly between members and entrepreneurs or through our VA Fund 1. In Edmonton, TEC VA runs two streams: a public and a private forum. Also within the TEC VA network are chapters in Calgary, Winnipeg, Kelowna and Phoenix (AZ) which run monthly Private forums. A new addition to the network now include satellite chapters in Medicine Hat and Prince George. These satellites will hold biannual events that are a mix of investor education and entrepreneur pitches.. Mission: Committed to building Western Canadian industry through early stage angel investing. Mission is to create and grow both quality investors and quality deal flow through mentorship, education events, a robust network. Our members also volunteer with multiple incubators in the communities we are active in to help support our community: · Venture Mentoring Services (Edmonton) · ICS Prince George · Start Up Edmonton · eHub, Falling Walls (UofA) · AccelerateYYC · NAIT · Innovate Manitoba · Entrepreneurship Manitoba · Grupo Guayacan

The network is more than the monthly meetings. There’s networking events, entrepreneur education events, promotion of private investing as an asset class, and an informal concierge service to entrepreneur resources). These activities provide a conduit for entrepreneurs and investors to connect with each other and create a healthy relationship that is essential prior to any investment.

Our plan is to continue to support the existing 5 chapters and then add in the 2 or 3 new satellites into our group. Our new fund, VA Angel Fund 1, will also allow for syndication of more deals and we expect this to ramp up in 2016.

Manitoba Knights
We invest in Manitoba-based opportunities. We invest into technology companies including IT and med tech. We invest into pre-revenue and early revenue companies.

Harry Ethans, 204-295-3059, 300-136 Market Ave. Wpg MB R3B 0P3, Corporate history in mergers and acquisitions for CanWest Global. Currently Deal Validator for Knights investments. Active on +5 Boards.
Steve Kroft, Chair. David Asper Noli Manalo

The Manitoba Knights are an organized group of individual investors, each sharing their opinions, but making individual investment decisions. All deals presented to the Manitoba Knights have met the investability criteria the group has established, and these criteria have been confirmed as present by Marshall Ring, CEO of the Manitoba Technology Accelerator, then Harry Ethans, Deal Validator for Manitoba Knights, and then a deal champion from the Knights. At this point, an investment meeting is called and investors are asked to declare interest or disinterest within 5 days.. Mission: Vision: That Manitoba-based technology companies have the ability to secure up to $3M in Angel financing and the opportunity to thrive and build deep roots in Manitoba. Mission: To provide Angel investors the opportunity to invest into high growth potential companies that have been screened by professional technology commercialization executives, as well as a peer group.

The organization currently has an operating budget of $0. We believe there is an opportunity to grow our footprint, aligned with the same goals as NACO through this project, but the Knights can operate on $0 and be effective.

The Manitoba Knights have an emerging collaborative relationship with the Saskatchewan Capital Network. Through this project application we would like to finalize and formalize the activities to support this relationship. The Knights also have informal collaboration with two lead Angel groups in Boston – Mass Medical and Hub Angels. Emerging relationships are also forming in China. This proposal includes finalization and formalization of those collaborative relationships.

Project: Quarterly meetings to explain investment process. Project alignment: Investor focused event; Membership recruitment and activation; Local marketing initiative. Impact on Goals: Increase the number of Angels in group; Connect members to other investors not in group; Increase the number and quality of educational and networking events. Activity Description: Knights investment process enables individuals with little experience in Angel investing in general, or technology investing specifically to invest as a result of the Knight’s screening process. Knight’s process also leverages other capital tools such as the Province’s Angel Tax Credit program. There are investors who want to understand the Knights approach to investing. Quarterly meetings can educate investors on our process and possibly convert into active Angels.

Project: Quarterly meetings to update on active investments. Project alignment: Investor focused event; Membership recruitment and activation; Local marketing initiative. Impact on Goals: Increase the number of Angels in group; Connect members to other investors not in group; Increase the number and quality of educational and networking event; Better reporting data. Activity Description: During quarterly meetings, report on active investments. Based on current track record, share prices of investments are rising. Communicating these results will encourage participation.

Project: Host celebration events for local investees on milestones. Project alignment: Investor focused; Membership recruitment and activation; Local marketing initiative. Impact on Goals: Increase the number of Angels in group; Connect members to other investors not in group; Increase the number and quality of educational and networking events; Better data to be reported. Activity Description: When key milestone events are realized, publicize the news and host celebration events. As an example, securing a first customer, securing a follow on round. The purpose is to celebrate success to encourage more participation.

Project: Review and compare current Knights’ tools and processes against good practices. Project alignment: Development of tools and resources. Impact on Goals: Connect members to other investors outside membership; Improve investor participation in deal syndication; Improve adoption of best practices; Better data to be reported. Activity Description: Identify leading good practices, look for commonality, compare and contrast to Knights, gap analysis and discussion on implementing improvements. If similar language and processes can be used, this will also increase syndication. Included is participation in events for collaborative groups, specifically Saskatchewan Capital Network.
Southern Alberta/Lethbridge Angel Network

Lethbridge’s population is 94,800 with two post- secondary institutions. It is located in the southern portion of the Alberta and is the centre of a trading area that serves approximately 275,000 people in Alberta, British Columbia and the State of Montana. In 2015, it was named one of the top 21 finalists for the designation of 2016 Intelligent Community of the Year. As well, CFIB rated Lethbridge18 out of 121 Canadian cities as the best place to start and grow a business. Lethbridge is home to tecconnect (est. 2011) the only technology business incubator south of Calgary. tecconnect currently supports 7 startup technology companies with 5 graduates. The local regional innovation network (RINSA) has been identified as a best practice in Alberta by AITF because of our collaborative and comprehensive approach to developing a robust entrepreneurial ecosystem.

She also organizes and delivers, through leveraged community and provincial partnerships, educational workshops, seminars and meetings for the benefit of all entrepreneurs in the community. Renae is also an entrepreneur having started, operated three companies; sold two and blew one up! She is also a leading member of the Regional Innovation Network of Southern Alberta (RINSA) ensuring collaborations between community partners, including both post-secondary institutions, are occurring in support of an entrepreneurial ecosystem in southern Alberta.

EDL also owns and operates tecconnect, a business incubator targeting startup companies in technology and innovation. www.tecconnect.ca

CapitalRoad is a National Not For Profit Foundation. The Foundation does not make investments, rather operates forums for active venture investors to meet Canada’s most promising companies. Over our 20 years of operating these forums we have often worked with angel organizations to facilitate the development of their networks and the ability for them to introduce promising companies to new investors. We also design our events to provide both investors and entrepreneurs with timely and relevant insights to improve the opportunities for everyone’s success.. Mission: To link Canada’s highest potential, emerging technology companies to the most active and supportive investors. CapitalRoad’s portfolio of events is recognized across Canada as the premiere showcase and networking platform for technology entrepreneurs. The Forums are a fixture on the calendars of the technology entrepreneur, Angel investor, and VC communities and are core drivers of a vibrant entrepreneur, Angel and institutional investor ecosystem.

The Foundation is a sustainable organization today. CapitalRoad is a national not-for-profit foundation committed to improving the opportunities for early and growth stage Canadian technology companies to better access investment financing. CapitalRoad is pleased to endorse the efforts of the Canadian venture capital and technology communities and is the proud operator of the Banff Venture Forum, Canadian Financing Forum and PROPEL Energy Tech Forum. These events represent Canada's largest investment forum operation, and are aimed at enhancing the access to capital environment for Canadian technology entrepreneurs Our events gather over 800 investors, entrepreneurs and service providers annually to showcase 75 of Canada’s leading emerging companies.

We have extensive engagement and support from the venture investment community, corporate venture investors and service providers in Canada. We have had many active efforts over the years to support stronger linkages between angel and venture networks and we are seeking additional partnerships to continue this work with the angel community. We want to collaborate with NACO to strengthen the relationships and deal flow between Angel Networks and venture investors by extending our Ambassador program to Angel Networks in Canada, helping them advance leading opportunities from their networks to meet new investors.

Angel and VC Education Webinar – a recorded webinar that would feature active angel networks and venture investors providing advice on how to best collaborate to maximize value and minimize risks for all parties. Once recorded, it can serve as a standard educational asset that NACO and Capitalroad could use to distribute to NACO supported angel networks and Capitalroad Ambassador Program Organizations across Canada. Proposed Timeline – Completed by September 2016 Budget - $10,000; NACO Contribution $5,000

Capitalroad Ambassador Program Extension – Assist with the promotion and expansion of the Ambassador Program. Key value for NACO Angel Networks 1. Place high growth potential companies from their network on a national stage in front of the highest caliber venture capital, venture debt, and other private equity investors along with corporate venture groups from top North American strategic acquisition companies; 2. Receive individual and organizational profile on the Forum websites and print programs; and 3. Leverage the Forums as a means of furthering the mandates of their respective organizations. Proposed Timeline – 2016-2017 Budget - $30,000 per annum; NACO Contribution $15,000 per annum

NACO Angel Network Attendance at CapitalRoad events. Subsidize or sponsor the costs of a leading opportunity in 10 NACO Supported networks to attend the Banff Venture Forum. The funds would support a NACO Angel Network lead angel or their best company of the year. Proposed – 2016-2017 Budget – 10 NACO Organizations x 1 Attendees x Admission Fees x 2 years = $25,900

Keiretsu Forum is a global investment community of accredited private equity angel investors, venture capitalists and corporate/institutional investors. Our worldwide network of capital, resources and deal flow spans across 41 chapters on 3 continents. Keiretsu Forum NW is headquartered in Seattle, WA and is comprised of 7 chapters in Seattle, Kirkland, Vancouver/Victoria BC, Portland, Boise and Tacoma. Each chapter has its own President who is an experienced angel investor and respected community leader acting as the liaison between the local startup communities and the Keiretsu Forum network. Since its inception in 2005, Keiretsu Forum NW members have invested more than $249M into 350+ startup companies including $41.9M into 57 companies last year. The companies that apply to present at Keiretsu Forum are looking to raise go-to-market funding between $250k-$5M and are commonly in their seed, series a, or series b round of fundraising. We have a robust screening process that reviews 30-50 company applications each month, 7-10 of which are reviewed and voted on by members for approval to present to each Northwest chapter. Once approved, companies travel to Tacoma, Vancouver BC, Kirkland, Seattle and Portland throughout a week and receive exposure to the 400+ investors throughout the Northwest in addition to having a live stream broadcast of their presentation to our chapters in Boise and Victoria. After the presentations, we offer a stringent due diligence process in which members considering investment produce thorough 80-300pg reports breaking down each component of the companies. Historically, 78% of the companies that complete a due diligence report with Keiretsu Forum NW receive funding, and in 2015 members completed 34 due diligence reports. Keiretsu Forum NW also provides due diligence training and educational workshops for members, partners and guests in collaboration with speakers to offer insight on relevant market trends and topics centered on the startup world and angel investing. Recent topics have featured intellectual property, exit strategy, competitive intelligence, estate tax planning, and how to analyze a marketing plan in due diligence. . Mission: “Great Association with Quality Deal Flow.” “Great Association… Keiretsu Forum membership is comprised of angel and institutional investors, business leaders, venture capitalists and serial entrepreneurs. Keiretsu Forum enjoys synergies and close relationships with venture capital firms, universities and other partner organizations. These relationships facilitate the access to capital, talent, technology and resources needed to build a successful venture. …With Quality Deal Flow.” Our quality and diverse deal flow comes from our community of members, venture capitalists, sponsors, incubators and universities. Keiretsu Forum members invest in early-stage companies that focus on emerging technologies, life science/healthcare, real estate, hardware, software, digital media and entertainment, social/environmental impact, fashion, mobile/wireless, clean technology and other segments with high growth opportunity.

In February 2016, Keiretsu Forum NW launched a new chapter in Tacoma and plans to roll out chapters in Arizona, Utah and Alaska in 2017 and 2018. Being headquartered in Seattle, we seek to grow our other Northwest chapters by enlisting more partners to source deals and add a full-time Director position for our chapter in Vancouver/Victoria BC. CIN is now a non-profit organization, dedicated to providing investor education, deal flow and other resources to connect and enhance the sophistication of the local investment community and has spurred new investments from local investors. Over the last two years, we have had a number of successful company exits. There now exists an excellent opportunity to further accelerate the growth and impact of our investor and company networks based on the combined outcomes provided by CIN, VIATEC as well as new collaborative projects with local angels.. Mission: Based on the groundwork laid by CIN, VIATEC and numerous successful technology entrepreneurs, the Victoria Angel Network provides a united approach to nurturing and growing Victoria’s angel investment community, increasing the number of participants in that community, and the amount of investments made in local companies. Victoria Angel Network investors share the common goal of achieving above-market returns by investing in local businesses, and by building community by actively participating in company screenings, education, forums, deep-dive reviews, meticulous due diligence, and ongoing support of the companies.

VIATEC has 4 years of matching funding available through NRC-CAIP (Canadian Accelerator and Incubator Program), in addition to revenues received through sponsorship and event registration fees. Victoria Investment Ecosystem Survey Angel investing is high risk and requires expertise and in-depth involvement for strong deal flow, screening and due diligence, and management and support of portfolio of tech start-ups. The Mean Eyed Cat is a Manitoba non-share capital corporation governed by two boards. The first board covers the accelerator portion of the Cat and consists of members with experience helping entrepreneurs through the development process. Companies going through this process have either received investments from the Angel group, an individual Angel or are in the process of seeking Angel funding. In keeping with Cat’s goals of building networks and providing the best possible support, this board consists of people from Manitoba, other locations in Canada plus international representatives. One of the Canadian representatives is Ross Finlay from the First Angels Network in Halifax. The second board consists of active Angels or key advisors to Angels in Manitoba. Three members of the accelerator board, Ross Finlay, Laura Kilcrease and Harry Yuklea serve as resources to the Angel board based on their experiences as Angel investors and VC’s. The Managing Director works with each group and keeps them informed of available deals plus the progress of the accelerator participants. Marshall Zacharias serves on both boards based on his entrepreneurial and investment experience. The Mean Eyed Cat’s network consists of investors from the Selkirk, Virden, Steinbach, Winkler and Brandon areas of rural Manitoba plus groups in Winnipeg representing a variety of ethnic groups including the Filipino, Chinese and Mennonite communities. . Mission: To develop the experiences of members and knowledge of the Angel asset class in Canada. The Mean Eyed Cat will accomplish this by: Building a diverse group of Angels from across the Province; Delivering education programs to build the skills of members; Allowing members to share experiences via regional and province-wide events, Developing relationships with other Angel groups in Manitoba and Canada to learn best practices; Developing relationships with US-based Angel groups to learn best practices; Syndicating deals as a way to improve both deal flow and allow for larger investments; Regularly attending NACO’s regional and national events; Actively supporting NACO’s activities and development; Working with Government to inform and develop programs to improve the Angel asset class; Developing relationships with the VC and other communities to develop exit plans; Working with local companies to ensure they are fully prepared to approach Angels; Working with the media and other publics to ensure they are familiar with the Angel asset class and the role Angels play in the capital markets.

The sustainability of the network relies on three things: Recruitment of new members: The Cat is constantly working with existing members to identify prospects. These are typically people making investments but not identifying themselves as Angels. The Cat also identifies people not making investments but meeting the characteristics of an Angel. This process is also designed to broaden the diversity of the group to include more women, younger members and groups from other demographic areas be it ethnicity or geographic. Education: By delivering an education program, the Cat aims to produce a more informed and disciplined investor. The goal is to build an investor’s skills so they adopt a portfolio approach and perform more due diligence. Providing these skills should prevent them from becoming disappointed and quit making investments after one or two don’t pan out. Part of this process also involves the power of networking with other groups and syndication. Exits: Members must see there is a history of realizing gains in their investments within a reasonable time period.

The Mean Eyed Cat has already started working with other groups in Western Canada, other regions in Canada and the US. In Western Canada, we have shared deals with the local chapter of the VAAngels and members of the Manitoba Knights as well as local Super Angel Jim Richardson and have been provided with information on deals by these groups. We have also reached out to the Saskatchewan Capital Network and are in the process of bringing in a presenter from BC, Basil Peters, to deliver a seminar on the issues involved with cross-border investments. Across Canada, we have collaborated with the Northern Ontario Angels, First Angels and Maple Leaf Angels. This collaboration has taken a variety of forms including offers to syndicate (Northern Ontario), sharing deals (FAN and Maple Leaf) and bringing in a speaker (FAN). Cross Border we work with a variety of groups based in North Dakota including the Dakota Venture Group. We also have developed ties with the Rice Alliance, Central Texas Angels and other groups in Texas.

Education Workshops: The Mean Eyed Cat will offer the NACO Academy sessions in Manitoba. We will start with the sessions on due diligence, building the network, mentoring; and exit strategies as well as the session targeted at entrepreneurs. Our plan is to offer three to four sessions per year, depending on demand. Eventually we will offer all sections of NACO Academy. In addition we will work with the Province to deliver workshops on the programs they offer that aid Angel investors, for example, the Small Business Venture Capital Tax Credit, Commercialization Support for Business and Manitoba Innovation Growth Side Car Fund. All education sessions will be open to other Angel groups in Manitoba as well as those from Northwestern Ontario, Saskatchewan, North Dakota, NW Minnesota and NE Montana.

Resource Tools: The Mean Eyed Cat will create an online library of resources the members can access as well as a common platform for receiving and sharing deals. The common platform we are leaning towards is AngelList but we also have experience with Gust. The proposed library would include articles on the industry or written by Angels from other regions in Canada or the US, sample forms, contacts in areas such as accounting, law, HR, VC firms and other specialty areas as well as forms the Angel can use as part of their due diligence or investment management process. It will also include case studies of previous investments to draw on the experiences of the Angels involved in these investments.

Membership Drives: The Mean Eyed Cat will undertake three major membership drives. The first is to locate and recruit women entrepreneurs from the City of Winnipeg. We are starting this drive in Winnipeg because of the population size, number of women-owned businesses and presence of a strong financial sector. The second drive will concentrate on the Parkland District (west side of Lake Manitoba) and Northern Manitoba as this region is currently not represented in the Mean Eyed Cat’s group but is increasingly important. Third, we intend to recruit members from the First Nations that have an active investment group, e.g. Peguis and Norway House as well as other Aboriginal groups. These groups are currently not represented in the Cat but are also becoming quite active. We are also looking to expand our base among our current demographics and reach out to other underrepresented groups, e.g., the LGBT community.

Regional Events – Syndication The Cat proposes to deliver a maximum of two such events per year and plans to tie these into the educational component. These events will include; meetings between the Mean Eyed Cat’s members and other groups in Manitoba; meetings with groups from Northern Ontario and Saskatchewan as well as groups from Northern Minnesota, North Dakota and Eastern Montana. The goals are: Build a level of trust between the groups via social activities; Share experiences and practices through seminars and case studies; Syndicate deals by running pitch sessions where each group brings along one or more companies to present.
Invest-Tech

The Invest-Tech has a wide range of members including individual Angels, members of local investment groups including the A-100, fund representatives, and family offices. We have junior investors as well as seasoned Angels who volunteer for the practice panel. Our membership is interested in a variety of industries like Oil & Gas although it is light at this time, agriculture and digital media.

Invest-Tech a program and service offered by Innovate Calgary. Our program line includes entrepreneur boot camps, practice pitch panels and forums for companies as well as Investor Education events throughout the year. . Mission: The mission of Invest-Tech is to assist in creating a capital market for Alberta tech deals by introducing well prepared deals to accredited investors.

The Invest-Tech team plans to allocate 80% of their resources to the current program with an increase of collaboration with neighboring angel groups for deal flow and to reduce the cost on things like major speaking events. The other 20% will be allocated to identifying high potential deals and providing a focused and custom program to increase invisibility. We also plan to provide more focused Investor education and recruitment events to increase networking and to identify new up and coming Alberta Angels.

Invest-Tech is in the early stages identifying other Angel groups within Alberta and our neighboring provinces to identify the interests of their Angel groups and to look at ways we can work together to better educate and get Angels involved. This will include Edmonton and Saskatchewan initially and move further east and west as we build momentum.

Marketing roadshow in Edmonton, Calgary, Regina and Saskatchewan and increase Invest-Tech visibility nationally The funds would be allocated to cover hard travel costs of the Invest-Tech team to travel within and outside of Alberta to meet and lock in new capital sources that are not current members. We believe there are groups and investors in smaller Alberta cities like Lethbridge, Medicine Hat and Olds that are not being fully engaged or supported with the current programming in Alberta. Through an Alberta tour, we plan to unlock new capital sources, provide education and networking support as well as increase the Invest-Tech membership. This focus of this project would not only be to educate and bring these new investors into the fold. This collaborative effort would create new capital pools for Invest-Tech deals but also offer investor education to those towns and cities. A second focus of this project would be work closely with offices like Economic Development Lethbridge, include their staff in the same education offering and develop a syndication relationship. These working relationship will offer Invest-Tech access to deals from other sources as well as offer deals from these cities and towns access to Invest-Tech member capital. A long term benefit of this project should see the formation of capital groups in these cities or towns. Throughout the 2016 calendar year, the Invest-Tech team plans to hold several investor education events in Calgary and is planning a marketing roadshow in Edmonton, Calgary, Regina and Saskatchewan. These events will serve as an informal member recruitment event in all 4 cities where investors and entrepreneurs in the community are all welcome to attend. There will be an education component and could potentially include a topic from the NACO academy. A second large and formal investor education event will be planned in Calgary early 2017 but depending on financing may include additional cities. In Calgary, we are planning 4 investor education events. The model of these events are to connect industry experts (speakers/panelists) with our members. This offers our members multiple benefits: Opportunity to network amongst each other Opportunity to network with industry experts Education on new markets or deals that may not be included in their portfolio These events offer several benefits to Invest-Tech as well including: Recruitment for new members Sales to for prospective members Creation of a more capable/skillful membership Retention of all members Invest-Tech plans to offer an education series with neighboring cities such as Edmonton and Regina or Saskatoon. The series would engage the angel groups in each city providing the same benefits as the Calgary members. The intention of this series is to engage their local offices like the VA Angels in Edmonton and Saskatchewan Capital Group. The hope is if we work together as offices our syndication relationships will improve but also by increasing the skillset and knowledge of members in each city it allows Invest-Tech deals access to additional capital pools. Finally, to increase Invest-Tech’s visibility within the Canadian Angel community some of the ask will be applied to allow for additional travel to Canadian Angel conferences and events like the NACO summit, the GROW conference or the annual Banff Venture Forum. An increase attendance at these events will allow for a larger deal syndication reach by providing the opportunity to network to continue work with other Angel group attendees. It will also provide an increased visibility of the programs and services offered by Invest-Tech as well as an increase exposure to the entrepreneurial community within Canada. Brand exposure at these types of events is crucial to the new Invest-Tech brand. Invest-Tech launched as it’s own brand separate from Alberta Deal Generator and has not had the opportunity to present itself to other angel groups. We want to build relationships with other Angel groups for several reasons: deal syndication but also Angel referrals. If a member of the Invest-Tech team has a contact in a different city looking for an Angel group, it is useful to one understand which group represents which city and their contacts and to understand their models. The same would be expected that these Angel groups understand the Invest-Tech model and refer their Calgarian contacts to Invest-Tech. These types of relationships are best formed at conferences or summits where Angel groups have opportunities to meet and establish a basic working relationship.
